Bakala's tenant: Heating in the stove, agreed to the rent increase
The old man walked out of the door of the client center of RPG Flats Company, owned by the 'coal baron' Zdenek Bakala, the largest privately owned rental apartment owner in Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried a folder with new lease contracts to three flats: his, his daughters and his son.
All three's rent has already risen due to deregulation.
Next year the son will be paid CZK 4100 for second class 2 +1 apartment instead of current CZK 3500 per month.
The man points his finger on his son's new contract, which he is authorised to sign by proxy.
"But I signed it," he says half angrily, half resignedly.
BytyOKD.cz Civic Association, which identified the new tenancy conditions as "unfair and immoral" advises tenants not to sign the new contract and wait until 7 December for guidance on how to counter them.
The man remains skeptic.
One says this, another that, he laughs.
Ostrava has become a great laboratory of deregulation.
After New Year the vast majority of non-market rented buildings in Czech Republic will be subject to deregulation.
Anyway, Aktuálněcz decided to visit the laboratory itself.
Havířov's RPG waiting room is one of four in the Ostrava region and is already full at nine a.m. on Tuesda.
Looking right at the door, there is a security guard from a security agency with a call device nearby.
Special button "Rent 2011" shines on the touch screen.
One tap and the machine issues a number.
You cannot even read "157" and your figure swirles on the large screen below the ceiling of the waiting room.
It is your turn in half a second.
The old couple comes to ask about the lease after a few moments, and there is no rush for new leases in the waiting room.
Most people came to solve the same problems as usual - request for repairs, insurance events etc.
Letters with new leases have been sent to mailboxes of most of the tenants of the 44 thousand dwelling RPG portfolio in Ostrava region since mid November.
RPG Byty proposes to increase rent by 15 to 38 percent in these letters.
Special desk for new leases was opened on 18 November in the client centre.
The clerks at the desk laugh, when the client introduces himself as a journalist.
Deregulation and Bakala's former mining flats are local hot topic.
Before the election it was quite loudly adopted by Parliament Vice President and a native of Ostrava Lubomir Zaoralek of the Social Democrats, and now it fills local newspapers.
"I have been asking them for this new floor for twenty years."
The man mentioned in the introduction says, "They have not even changed a f..king plate in the bathroom," says the man mentioned in the introduction.
It is mostly retired people who only come to see if they can get a discount on rent if they sign on time, as they promise to fulfil their promises in their special offer.
Half off February rent will also be paid to the other tenants who have signed the new contract by 15 December.
Havířov's "deregulatory desk" is certainly not overloaded with questions.
"Out of yesterday's 360 clients about twenty to fifty came to inquire about leases in 2011," says the counterclerk.
RPG on their bulletin board and Web site proposed individual contracts where needed.
However, if the parties fail to agree on the lease, an independent tribunal will have to establish the rent.
This is not a threat, but the only legitimate and completely legal procedure.
"Nobody will sue them here," said one of the RPG Flats clerks and the man on the street outside the client center partly agrees.
Because I have CZK 13,000 pension and five thousand left for the meals I cannot afford bringing it to court.
The clerk but then does not doubt after all.
"We will see."
Because Mr Zaoralek advises them not to sign, so some people are waiting.
The regulation of rents ends in most Czech Republic with the New Year 2011 and according to RPG Byty the increase of rents is an economic necessity.
The current rent is still below the amount needed for simple maintenance of housing stock, according to Pavel Klimes, Director of RPG portfolio of residential apartments, and reminded that neglect of the housing stock complaints from angry tenants is the main reason for the increase in rents according to house owners.
While in five years between 2005 and 2010 RPG could invest four billion from the rents into the apartment, in four years between 2011 and 2014 it should be 5.2 billion.
Large screen hanging from the ceiling opposite the padded seats of Havířov's waiting room keeps repeating some information highlighted in red.
"The increase in rents in 2011 by 15% and less concerns 31,200 flats, it is more than 90% of RPG apartments."
"And it will always be a maximum of CZK 7.50 per square meter and month," appears on the screen.
Only for 400 apartments of the RPG portfolio the rent will rise by 38 percent.
In these cases the increase will be from an extremely low CZK 19.66 per square meter to an increase of CZK 19.66 per square meter.
In 2600 apartments will the rent remain the same next year.
RPG Byty promise that rent deregulation will not be sudden, it will be spread over four to eight years.
It adds another commitment: all the money from rent increases (see chart) will be invested in the flats, especially in heat savings - new windows and insulation.
Priority will be given to people who sign the agreement to increase rents.
Offices need a kindergarten, architects have understood.
Avriopoint Office Building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design Company.
Nobody would expect that it contains a small kindergarten with everything necessary - with coloured walls, imaginative furniture, a bunch of toys and even a mini golf course on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year children of Arch.Design employees can attend.
Architectural design company, Arch.Design, whose studios produced many important buildings in Brno, have included the space for their corporate kindergarten in the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
It employs nearly 90 people - mainly baby-boom-aged and they want their women designers and architects to quickly return to work.
The possibility of part-time contracts is also available for Arch.Design employees.
Female construction engineers and architects have thus the opportunity to mix their demanding jobs with child care.
Tinz kindergarten was created by Arch. Design employees themselves and with support from management they were able to obtain a grant from the European Union and the Labour and Social Affairs Ministry.
Corporate tiny kindergarten is funded by the European Social Fund through the Operational Program Human Resources and Employment and the Czech state budget.
The grant funding (subsidy of 2.8 million) was able to purchase equipment and for two years provide qualified personnel and operation.
After the depletion of financial aid (2 years) the Arch.Design Company must operate the kindergarten for 3 years at its own cost.
Preparation of the project lasted one year and the Economy Rating Company helped with the application for grant.
The care is provided by qualified staff, children are taken care of by nurse and kindergarten teacher all day, but most children are over 3 years old.
This is a "Mini-kindergarten" and only 5 children may be present at the same time, though more can attend in the course of the day.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible to the needs of parents and children of all employees have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of their position in the company hierarchy.
Although this is an individual education and care, the program content in the mini-kindergarten is similar to the framework program of preschool education.
Children are not only playing here, they are also provided with quality teaching - from basic knowledge to schooling and English is also taught here.
The class is not only equipped with toys, inspiring games, but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of children directly in the company promotes a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can always check their child and prevent stress situations related to delayed pick up from nurseries located far from their parents' work place.
Parents then use their working time much more effectively.
It is unexpected that a loyal employee -employer relationship is produced there naturally.
Arch.Design became one of Czech companies that offer significant benefit when recruiting new employees, they are friendly to family and through this program they have enhanced personnel marketing.
The House of bones still fascinates after 100 years. Look at the interiors by Gaudi
The roof looks like a prehistoric lizard's spine, the staircase reminds of a dinosaur backbone and balconies are open fish mouths.
This is the house of Casa Batlló in Barcelona by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
The locals started calling it the Bone House for its organic shapes.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, broken tiles and mosaics, a huge facade with scales and soft curves, all of which are typically of the Gaudí Art Nouveau.
The house opens with dreamy lines, soft colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
The detailed look reveals geometry, rhythm, and well-considered order.
At night, the whole house appears even more dramatic, it is lit to enhance the gloss paint impression.
Winding and twisting shapes are equally as common indoors.
Wood follows the window frames in the wave, along with handrails, door trim and watch.
Batlló House, located in the Eixample district on a busy shopping street Passeig de Gracia No 43, was rebuilt from the original house in 1877 by the architect Emilio Sal Cortes.
Reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, a wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on the demolition of the old building and building a new one, but soon he adopted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper redevelopment of the house.
The apartment building Casa Batllo was never designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
Architect Josep Maria Jujol cooperated with him.
It was his developer board that created the decorations for the representative apartment of the property owner, as well as the use of mosaic on the facade.
Other authors and artists worked on the facade.
Joint work on draft plans for Casa Batlló building started a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol was involved in the construction of Gaudi's building Casa Mila and Park Guell, which contains other Gaudi works.
The locals started calling it the "House of Bones" for its organic shapes.
Others began to call it a "yawning house" for its specific mechanism of opening windows.
It is also reported that on the top of the building there is a representation of the sword of St. George, the patron of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the building also contain hidden religious motives.
Gaudi designed a central heating system in the house, unique for his time, with ventilation and typical chimneys.
Their forty five degree slope may seem bizarre.
When creating Gaudi totally ignored building regulations of the time and could not allow them to tie him.
The start of construction he received a building permit from the city, but the details of the planned reconstruction were so limited that two years later the City Council asked for redress.
Councilors often noticed that the building could interfere with its pillars into the public sidewalk.
The correction never occurred, but rather the opposite: only fifteen days after the request from the city, Josep Batlló applied for (and successfully received) the permission to lease the top two floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to lower floors.
The gallery was on the second floor and on the third floor there was a bedroom and a private section of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry company.
The whole six-storey building is intersected by a staircase, which ends only at the roof terrace.
The key elements of the reconstruction were the elimination of all right angles and straight lines and replacing them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space interconnection.
The social part is completely connected by opening the saloon door and a large group can comfortably communicate without leaving the privacy for intimate conversations.
The house won due to Gaudi's rebuilding a new facade and also the unusual roof and two extra floors.
Also, Gaudi’s play with light is remarkable, along with blue and white glazed tiles used to line the inner courtyard and skylights.
The play of two colors ensures maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was enough to gamble on the principle that white reflects light more than dark colors, which absorb the sun's rays on the contrary.
Casa Batlló House, which was included in UNESCO World Heritage Fund in 2005, is open to all.
The most spacious and most luxurious apartment has been opened to the public on the first floor.
The owners decided to move this up in 2002 to celebrate the one hundred fiftieth anniversary of the birth of the famous author.
They kept providing the excursions since they discovered that this is a very profitable business, and they extended the tours by the common and attic spaces, including a roof terrace.
The admission to the sight is quite low, costing 16.50 euros, while students, seniors and travel passport holders receive a ten percent discount.
The amount greatly exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudi's buildings in the city.
If you want to experience the true atmosphere of the house with dragon towers, you must quickly make friends with any of the apartment house's residents and visit them at home.
