People monitoring devices are increasingly needed by parents who want to watch their children.
Fear for their own child is a major reason for using GPS.
The system originally created to search for cars also monitors people and thus should help in cases such as the disappearance of nine-year-old Annie Janatková.
The facility is currently of size of a matchbox, but it may soon be as large as a watch.
Many people have been scared by the case of missing Annie and thus began to search for better ways to protect their children.
Even at the cost of disruption to their privacy.
They are not spying, but a way to reduce the likelihood of a tragedy occurring, said Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of surveillance equipment on the Czech market.
"I admit that under certain circumstances it may lead to misuse of such equipment if they are placed in a bag of someone who does not know it, but we have not seen such cases yet."
"Most customers actually buy it for security reasons," he added.
According to him, children should always know what the purpose of the box is and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková says if a child does not want to wear something like that, it will just get rid of it.
"Even young children show great creativity how to lose some things on purpose if they do not want to be under control."
Parents' expectations were fueled by cell phones before, but they can be switched off as well with this device.
According to her it is questionable whether such a device would really help.
"As for the upcoming kidnapping, the perpetrator always ensures that the child should not have any electronics that may reveal his position."
It's now.
When tracking devices get more common, they will look for them, because their sales will be supported by mass advertising.
In such cases, criminals are always one step ahead of police, says the psychologist.
The nurse does not believe that similar devices may help in sudden attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring Company, providing tracking services for both cars and people, even when the tracking device is attacked and immediately destroyed, it can help.
"The device can be set to send regular position report after a certain period of time."
If it becomes damaged, we will have at least the last position of the person.
The more expensive devices have inbuilt and tiltmeters, so even if one falls and remains motionless, the device immediately sends a warning with location.
According to him similar service may be provided by smart mobile phones with navigation, where it is sufficient to download a special software.
The problem of current surveillance units lies in the fact that it is either a device similar to matchbox pendants or smaller mobile phones.
There is always the risk of loss.
According to Pilin from Macro Weil Company a device that looks like a conventional digital watch is now being tested.
This will be the biggest advantage that the aggressor may not even recognise the tracking device at all.
They may recognise it after some time and it may give the police extra time.
While the tracking devices develop into bracelets or pendants, they still use the same technology used for monitoring vehicles.
It is a combination of location detection via GPS (used in regular car navigation) and the functions of a mobile phone, which reports the current position of the vehicle.
