Holding index finger longer than ring finger indicate a lower risk of cancer.
They have a longer index finger than the ring finger are at lower risk of prostate cancer.
It is a surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
This may be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
These results show that the finger length may be a simple test for prostate cancer risk, especially for a man up to 60 years old.
The finger could then help determine which men should undergo prostate cancer tests, particularly in combination with genetic risk or other threatening factors such as family health burden, she said.
In the period 1994-2009 she along with her colleagues monitored more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer in Britain and parallel over three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had a shorter index finger on their right hand than their ring finger.
The same probability of prostate cancer occurred for them as for 19 percent of those whose fingertips were of equal length.
The risk for infection in men over the age of sixty declined by 33 percent, and for men over the age of sixty it was even an 87 percent decline.
The ratio of the length of those two finger - formed in the prenatal period - probably reflects different levels of sex hormones that the child is exposed to in the womb.
Less testosterone usually results in a longer finger.
Previous studies have shown that testosterone is the key factor in prostate cancer development.
The geneticist and former Czech President of the Academy of Sciences Professor Vaclav Paces told ČTK that he knows about the study but in his opinion the relationship between fingerlength and cancer is not "fully proven."
