The first is Latin America's mild sunny mood.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its core institutions.
Support for democracy has risen noticeably in several countries on the Pacific rim of South America (see table 1).
In Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% a year since 2002, democracy support has risen from low of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also rose in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after a big drop in output last year.
The remaining half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries, are believed in democrats, which drags down the regional average (see chart 2).
Some 44% of respondents in the region reported themselves satisfied with how their country's democracy works in practice, a similar figure as last year but a big increase on the 25% in 2001.
Some 34% of respondents believed in their country's Congress and 45% in their government, which is still a similar year in both cases but up sharply from 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago economic challenges in Latin America undermined support for democracy.
The stability of the crisis is probably because many Latin American countries suffered only a short recession and have enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social safety net has helped protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty declined marginally in 2009 and has fallen again this year to 32%.)
The mood varies widely from country to country (see chart 4).
Brazilian economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a widely shared sense of progress.
The cases are rare in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and violent crime has worsened.
