Khmer Rouge veterans forced to confront past
In a dimly lighted concrete classroom with smudged and peeling walls, the principal of Anlong Veng High School remembered the man who built it, the late Khmer Rouge leader Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader, and he cared about his people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
The commander is still popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure and where thousands of the organization's former soldiers still live.
This year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge took the government, long held loyalties are finally challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum allowed victims to publicly confront people who participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook that first teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to children of its former soldiers.
In July, a joint U.N. and Cambodian tribunal handed out its first conviction of a former Khmer Rouge member, which sentenced the onetime head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each development, anxiety has grown among Anlong Veng's Khmer Rouge veterans, complicating reconciliation and reintegration into Cambodian society.
The former Khmer Rouge is a threat to any action, but they are unable to do anything.
Their life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil.
"It is creating divisions within families."
During the Khmer Rouge rule of Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, an estimated 1.7 million people were executed or died from starvation, disease or overwork.
The Vietnamese invaded and toppled the Pol Pot-led government in 1979, and the remaining military moved to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
Then they launched an insurgency that lasted until the last of the movement capitulated in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary directed the guerrilla war from their bases in western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated a following in Anlong Veng.
In mid-1990s, after a U.N.-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to withdraw from the government, resulting in the release of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had held out, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
The man died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while waiting for trial.
With no more donors providing for them, most former Khmer Rouge fighters have fallen into the grinding poverty common in rural Cambodia, and many remain nostalgic for the movement.
Although some elite Khmer Rouge officials kept their local government posts in exchange for laying down their arms, the rank and file remain poor, untrained farmers.
These people have little benefit after the surrender, according to Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which holds public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They are embedded with the utopian agrarian ideology of the regime."
"They were brought up with no concept of doing business."
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a young teenager in 1974, lived in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settle into a poor rice farmer in 1998.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
Ta Mok fed everyone.
"But now life is difficult because we have to provide for ourselves."
The current Khmer Rouge tribunal has also caused concerns here.
Early next year, the court is expected to begin trying Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan and his wife Ieng Thirith.
The court's mandate is to prosecute senior leaders and those most responsible for crimes, but it has not given any details on whether it will pursue cases beyond those four.
This has done little to calm fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was a district chief in Banteay Meanchey province in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers from the Documentation Center of Cambodia that she supervised construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project where thousands of forced laborers died.
In a recent evening, Im Chaem returned from working in the field to her wooden stilt house on the dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun spread long shadows across the parched grass, Im Chaem declined to discuss her past in the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she said she would not go.
"Cambodia is peace and stable," she said.
If more prosecutions occur, there will be war.
Chief Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that stability will occur if the court pursue more suspects, although experts and historians dispute that.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past," he has said.
However, confronting past is what Cambodia must do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the documentation centre.
"Reconciliation in Khmer terms is reconnecting the broken pieces," he said.
It is our obligation to put these broken pieces together so that we can understand.
The center produced the first government-approved textbook about the Khmer Rouge, the 75-page "A History of Democratic Kampuchea."
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Education Ministry's high school history textbook, which has less than four pages about the Khmer Rouge.
As in most Cambodia, Anlong Veng's young people do not know much about the Khmer Rouge, despite the town's connection to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook was a good way to learn about their history.
The parents react with skepticism when he took the book home to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the tribunal," he said.
The court is suspicious because they are not sure how many people the court will prosecute.
The resistance has made the process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
The public forums, the textbook and the tribunal are beginning to have impact, he said.
Still, the Khmer Rouge remains powerful in this region.
