Red Bull triumphs in F1 with its secret weapon: Siemens.
There is software that can design improvements to the cars in real time.
Since Red Bull entered the world of Formula 1 in 2004, its history in this select universe of speed has been marked by surprise and success.
Initially nobody considered the options of a new team, despite the ascending trajectory of the last seasons, last November, in the final race of the championship all betting on the victory of Fernando Alonso's Ferrari.
Without losing his reputation as champion driver, the German Sebastian Vettel, nor the power of the Renault motor that drives his car, in Formula 1 " the secret weapon that Siemens has placed into the hands of Red Bull to turn it into a winning team has become a legend.
It is a powerful simulation software that the German company started selling in 2007 with aims far away from high automobile competition.
Dedicated PLM, this powerful computer science instrument has been used to design assembly chains for manufacturing factories, energy plants, high precision instruments.
The aim is to reproduce, to faithfully simulate the product or process before constructing it in real mode, avoiding failures and avoidable costs.
Plm has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi airplanes and the most famous utilitarian cars of Nissan.
According to Russwurm, the use of this computer science instrument in his F1 factory has allowed Red Bull to design and make "in few hours, almost in time real" the modifications, changes and improvements needed during the races and tests.
Russwurm explains that the team in 1992 had an average of 10 technicians who could add a maximum of three or four improvements to the vehicles during every season.
Red Bull has 180 professional young people with high qualifications working today, equipped with powerful computer science equipment, analyse and project all kinds of modifications to the cars.
The Siemens manager explained that the software PLM is able to analyse and improve all elements of Red Bull cars except the engine, which is entirely Renault’s responsibility.
The materials, fuel, aerodynamics and security elements are being modified.
The changes can be made from the virtual reality of the simulator to the real world in 24 hours thanks to advanced production systems using high-tech laser and autoclaves.
The only limitation of this technological improvement is the figure of 40 million dollars that each Formula 1 team can spend at most every season to facilitate the competition.
Red Bull has built a high-tech factory for designing and producing its cars in a locality about 50 KM from London.
There are two buildings in which visits are restricted, especially for journalists.
The entire process is considered "Top Secret."
The factory has 580 employees, including two drivers, the champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
The Red Bull hero, without doubt, is recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
The huge technological resources that the energetic drink brand has given to its participation in the circuits, other players hide whose contribution is significant and their notoriety is unrecognized.
The head of technology at the factory, Steve Nevey, says that five years ago it was possible to affirm that I+D advances in the cars contributed to 50% of the victories and the driver was responsible for the rest.
Today these percentages have changed and technology adds 85% of the success, while the driver contributes with 15% of the value.
Nevey recognises that neither Vettel or Webber will never be replaced by computer science, because they are indispensable gladiators.
