Sport and fraud law
Alonso and Ramos before the Ajax shows wittiness but not the will to get removed from a sanction.
The probable expulsion of two Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the 23rd November match against Ajax in Champions League has caused rivers of written evidence about whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As we all know, a few minutes before the end of the game (which they had already won), both players deliberately wasted time, which made the referee show the second yellow card to both of them.
This way, and since Madrid will finish as the group leader, both players will fulfil the prescribed sanction in the next league game, against Auxerre, and will be able to get rid of the cards the following phase.
The Disciplinary Committee of the UEFA has awarded two games to the team’s manager, Jose Mourinho, and different economic amounts to the implied players.
The threat of yellow cards in similar circumstances as this one is not new practice, but is quite common in football.
It is so extended that it is part of the ethos, of unwritten rules, but followed nonetheless by this sport.
The main issue in the case is caused by the fact that it has been carried out by the team of the Real Madrid organization (which in its hymn claims nobility and honour, and has fined its players for similar acts) and by the dramatic sequence orchestrated by Mourinho, who adds one more to his extended arsenal of hysterical and provoking technician.
The debate is about if that type of behaviour not specifically prohibited by the regulation contradicts the sport principles, that is to say, if with such actions fraud is committed, then indeed they are respectful actions with the sport regulation, but they seem to blur its sense.
The matter examines the type of damage that is caused to the sporting spirit.
One of the advantages of the sport spirit is the physical integrity of the opposite players, aspect that with these actions was not threatened, that is to say, there was no violent game.
Other advantages to which the fare-play is referred to is to prevent that the lawbreaker team misuse the other team, which was not either.
The paradox of the action of the Madrid players is that they did not comply with what we normally characterize as legal fraud, because they did not act secretly to avoid the sanction, but they acted most explicitly to avoid the sanction.
They waited for and accepted the sanction with no complaints.
Other question is what type of advantage the violators acquired in deliberately carried out actions.
This is not a disadvantage for rival nor is a gain in the same game, because the result of the action would imply leaving their own team with less players.
The strategy is not useful for the next game, because the club will not be able to count on them.
The advantage, however, is that the players will start the next phase of the Championship without cards that could threaten their future participation.
It is a long term advantage with a certain degree of indeterminacy, as the team can be eliminated first of change and in addition they fulfil sanction game and go to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension by card accumulation occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
Then, by passing rounds it is not so clear that it is an advantage.
The actions are really against the sporting spirit, which is part of strategic decisions that favour taking advantage of the rules.
Regarding this assumption, the players did not act to prevent the application of the sanction (this would have been clear legal fraud), but rather chose when to obey it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding the punishment.
The border between wittiness and law fraud is diffuse, but in this occasion I believe it was a clear case of wittiness.
The controversy seems to arise from two factors: because it was about two auto expulsions and how the transmission of the directive was carried out to cause them.
The damage caused to the sport by these actions is not as much ethical as aesthetic.
