China maintains the objectives of reducing greenhouse effect gases.
The representative of that country at the COP16 reiterated that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the carbon track and detailed that his country will continue to maintain its offer to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45% by 2020.
China maintains its offer to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by between 40 and 45 percent by the year 2020, according to Su Wei, China's representative to the COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th UJ Conference on Climatic Change (COP16), Su Wei stressed that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the carbon track and re-convert its industry.
In fact, in the last four years his country has invested 245 million dollars in reducing its greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he reiterated that China will not change its objectives, but will continue working with the international community in that matter.
The Chinese strategy on climatic change is divided into four parts: dialogue; building capacities; building institutions and endorsement to pilot programs.
All those parts have been advanced, including the approval last year of a new Energy law with objectives regarding the reduction of gas emissions, he explained.
In China, the federal authorities have been working in a coordinated way with and the state and local authorities in order to achieve the objectives of energy saving, efficient energy use and reduce emissions.
In addition, there are already developed or completed multiannual plans, either funded by the Chinese government or by other countries.
The example is the Efficient Use of Energy Program, implemented in the last five years, with investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and the private initiative.
The project is also being developed for climatic change, one for the change of incandescent centres by economizers and another for mitigating and adapting, he added.
The same table, Martin Krol, the country's scientific adviser on climatic change, stressed that China's efforts have been much more than generally believed.
Examples are, the per capita greenhouse gas emission in China is six tons per person, whereas in the United States is 100 tons; China is responsible for the 9 percent of the historical contribution to greenhouse gas emissions.
Also, it has a without precedent effort in the use of the energy, increasing by 20 percent its energy efficiency over the last five years and anticipates to do the same in year 2020.
