EU changes the rules for obtaining the visa
Applicants will have to go to the Centres for Visa Applicants before their interview in the Consular Section, the cost will be smaller and so will waiting times.
From 10th January 2011 the procedure of issuing a visa in the Embassy of the United States and consulates will be altered.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to the attendance centres for Visa Applicants (ASC) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
The ASC staff will take the biometric information of the candidate, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section before the interview.
The new procedure will have many advantages for the applicants, among which:
The total cost of issuing the visa will be reduced, as there will no longer be a payment to get the appointment, another payment to process the request and another payment to the correspondence service will give the document.
The applicant will make only one payment for the three services.
The present tariff will remain unchanged, equivalent to 140 dollars for a tourist visa, 150 dollars for requests for visas (including visas for temporary workers), and 390 dollars for visas for retailers and investors.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but they will have to go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and have fingerprints taken.
Because the biometric information will be taken in the ASC, applicants who require a second date for being interviewed in the Consular Section will have to attend one less time than previously.
Also, those requesting a visa in the Consulates of Ciudad Juarez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra tariff on service of 26 dollars.
Additional information on the new procedure for asking for a visa can be found on the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQ.htm
