A global plan for renewing lighting.
Yesterday at Cancun UNO presented a plan for renovation of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries with a view to reducing almost onethird of the additional reduction needed to stabilise the planet's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is one of many concrete projects that UNO hopes to adopt at Cancun to counter the lack of mandatory reduction initiatives by industrialised countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if incandescent bulbs, which still hold 50% to 70% of the market, were replaced by fluocompact bulbs or better still by electroluminescent diode bulbs (DEL or LED in English), the bulk of the 1.8 million tonnes of GES emitted on the planet to provide human beings with light, would be avoided.
Illumination is responsible for 8% of worldwide emissions.
This is equivalent to 70% of the emissions by world's motor vehicles.
The highly emissions countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others including Canada, adopted voluntary reduction plans to reduce global GES emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
Then it will be necessary to add further 5 Gt to stabilise the increase of climate warming by 2020 at 2°C to prevent loss of control.
In incandescent bulbs 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and only the remaining 5% produce light.
With fluocompact bulbs, the dissipation of energy is reduced by 75% and with the new DEL bulbs, the energy requirement is also reduced by double that amount.
Fluocompact bulbs last on average between 6000 and 10 000 hours.
The new DEL bulbs, which have a life expectancy of 25 000 hours and consume 80% less energy than incandescent bulbs, give an idea of the saving that could be achieved in a 100 country replacement plan.
The newly developed bulbs also work with rheostats, providing little heat.
And they contain no mercury.
The experts have voiced a few negative opinions about fluocompact bulbs, because they contain mercury and because they are dangerous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless they issue instructions.
The main source of mercury emission on the planet is not fluocompast bulb, but carbon thermal emission centres, which emit a lot of mercury to produce the electricity wasted in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these centres emit 25 000 tonnes of mercury a year.
The report details the gains, which every country would achieve through this international programme.
Examples include Indonesia saving thousands of dollars a year on electricity and eight million tonnes of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 thermal centres, which costs 2.5 thousand million dollars.
