Climate: How France takes a swipe at its finance promises.
A year after the Copenhagen agreement it is time to look at the observance of the promise of fast finance (called fast start finance) by developed countries.
Large scale tampering appears.
The Copenhagen agreement requires developing countries to provide 30 million million dollars between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union promised 7.2 thousand million Euros over three years and France 1.25 thousand million Euros (420 million a year).
The European Union tried to convince its partners of the authenticity of its rapid start finance promise, submitting a report detailing its Member States’ action, Press Conferences, major side events, distribution of brochures...
The operational transparency is appreciated and valued at its right value: developing countries and the civil society are doing the same and at the same level of precision.
The European Union announces having allocated in 2010 2.2 million million Euros, a good token of observance of its promise of 7.2 million Euros in 2012.
Looking at details, things are more complicated.
This money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a supplementary effort is made without detrimental impacts on public development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement about what "new and additional" means.
The European Commission has proposed a harmonization, but some Member States have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses what suits him/her best.
The European Commission, for example, took for reference the year 2009; international finance is maintained and it adds 150 million over 3 years as fast start finance.
Other countries chose similar references in terms of year or level of public development assistance.
In contrast, France considers all 2010 new projects as "new and additional projects."
In other words, there is no reference to the previous years, or globally, of public development assistance.
Concretely, the total support given by France to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease) because France maintains that it is keeping its commitment in response to new and additional finance.
Other important element is the separation of gifts and loans.
There is no rule and everyone chooses his own method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that a Euro lent is equal to a Euro donated.
Clearly, this is difficult to justify; the effort is not coparable.
If the custom of loans can be justified for certain investments which are profitable (often projects linked to emissions which require more efficient technology) it is unreasonable to call a Euro which one will recoup as a donated Euro.
It needs only reason to recognize that it "observes" its commitments of 420 million Euros by making 91.5% of loans (399.8 million Euros) and 8.5% of donations (36,1 million Euros) - see European Union document for your own verifcation.
It is the only country in the Union to use loans on such a large scale.
Germany is lending 46%, while Denmark, The Netherlands and Slovak (among others) maintain their commitment with 100% as donations.
In other words, when the great majority of the European Union gives 1 Euro to meet its commitment, France only gives 10 centimes and regards its effort as similar.
A nice sleight of hand!
Summary: France operates in its fast start finance double blackmail: on one hand on the evolution of the action over time and on the reality of the financial effort.
By only spending 36.1 million Euros it believes that it is generating a belief that it is spending 420 million "new and additional" Euros as it promised.
The manipulation of the Finance Minister (because it appears that it is Bercy that implemented the arbitrage) could have double negative impacts, both within the European Union (why should other Member States continue to give if sufficient lending is available?) and in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not completely duped.
The early finance chapter is only a small, relatively short term matter in relation to all the discussions about climate change.
It can be popped more sand in the huge machine, the UNFCCC.
However, we hope that this is not the case.
In any case, it is essential to draw lessons from this first year of early finance.
First of all, France could announce a change in its accountancy method for 2011 and 2012 in order to honour its commitments and to equal equity with other European Union countries.
It is also possible to promote the discussions about long-term financing stakes (another crucial chapter currently discussed) but it is not possible to avoid the question of "additionality" or the method of accountancy of loans.
France could change its position to be as progresive on these stakes as it is on others.
The hope is based on the new Environment Minister, Ms Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Casun next week.
A surprise announcement on France's fast start and on the view of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase international confidence in progress in these discussions.
Alert on pesticides consumed by children.
Future Generations Association (formally Movement for Future Generations Rights and Respect) reports that a child of 10 consumes in one day 81 different chemical substances.
The association which predicts that its results do not have any statistical value, but indicate the problem being addressed has bought in markets of the Oise and Paris in July and September, the basket of foodstuffs generally consumed in four meals by a child of ten.
The meals included official recommendations, five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water, as well as delicacies, were examined in clinical research laboratories dealing with chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance sheet is staggering: 81 chemical substances, including 42 potentially or probably carcinogenic and five definitely carcinogenic, as well 37 substances able to induce endocrine disorders, according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
According to the Association, even if in most cases the legal limits of each chemical substance are not exceeded, our investigation shows that the reality of exposure to potentially carcinogenic contaminant is very concerning.
For breakfast, butter and milk alone contain over ten possible and three proven carcinogenic residues and almost twenty potentially damage the hormone system.
An apple from Brazil contains traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide, prohibited in France.
The same applies to beans from Kenya included in a luncheon, in which the study found traces of a powerful insecticide prohibited in the European Union.
In addiiton, minced steak, canned tuna, even a baguette and chewing gum contained pesticides and other chemicals.
Tapwater contained nitrates and chlorophyll.
The most chemically rich salmon steak was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues, and even the plastic plate used for warming the meal in the microwave was not exempted.
According to the study, the final risk for the consumer in this "contaminant cocktail" is probably underestimated.
